I agree with Paul and SW.  The remains need to be tested.  We now have the capability to do so, and the family needs to know.  What an honor for the family to know that their member has been honored by his country as the &quot;unknown&quot; for all these years.  <br><br>
I also have a proposal to make in case these remains are actually identified.  The remains of several of the Jolly 67 crew were buried in Arlington in a combined grave, as they could not be individually identified after over a year of trying.  These remains could possibly be used, with the agreement of the families involved, as the &quot;unknown.&quot;  We would know that they were from this crew, but we would not know exactly who it was.  <br><br>
This, in my opinion, would right another wrong, in that there was almost no press coverage of the Jolly 67 ceremony last November 19th.<br><br>
